load ../subworkflow-attestation.maude

--- Coverage: a package convergence-checks a tool, attests it eligible, and a
--- downstream grant is then accepted from the contract.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SUBWORKFLOW-ATTESTATION :
  convergent(t1) grants(t1)
  =>* C:Cfg accepted(t1) .

--- Coverage: a grant to a tool with no eligibility attestation is rejected.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SUBWORKFLOW-ATTESTATION :
  grants(t1) notAttested(t1)
  =>* C:Cfg rejected(t1) .

--- Bite: the trust boundary holds. A grant to a tool the package did not attest
--- is never accepted. The RESIDUAL soup var means an accepted state anywhere in
--- the reachable space is a solution, so No solution proves the consumer never
--- accepts a cross-package tool without a real eligibility attestation.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SUBWORKFLOW-ATTESTATION :
  grants(t1) notAttested(t1)
  =>* accepted(t1) RESIDUAL:Cfg .

--- Coverage: the genuine path serves BOTH consumers -- once a convergence-checked
--- tool is attested, the grant is accepted AND the tool is published downstream.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SUBWORKFLOW-ATTESTATION :
  convergent(t1) grants(t1)
  =>* C:Cfg accepted(t1) published(t1) .

--- Bite (the report-vs-check bug class): the SECOND consumer is held to the same
--- boundary. A tool the package did not attest is never published either, so a
--- trusted conclusion can never arise for an un-attested tool from ANY consumer.
--- An un-gated publish rule (publish from grants alone) would make published(t1)
--- reachable here and turn this No solution into a solution -- the regression bite.
search [1] in WHIPPLESCRIPT-SUBWORKFLOW-ATTESTATION :
  grants(t1) notAttested(t1)
  =>* published(t1) RESIDUAL:Cfg .
